node.text:
Siem Reap with the adjacent Angkor area, and all the temples including Angkor Wat, actually was the very first vacation only done for cultural reasons 😅

The first stop after my internship in Singapore was Cambodia, a friend from Germany joined me to travel for another 15 days 😁

Really incredible to see and hear the story behind this area and how everything plays together. Never knew that this region was a huge, flourishing ecosystem in the past, all temples being built, one for each of the Kings that ruled, while Angkor was thriving.

We only spent 3 days in Cambodia before we went off to Ho Chi Minh City.
Enough time to see the temples in detail and not get too used to them to lose appreciation for their magnificence 🌱 ✌️ #vegan #veganfood #govegan #maketheconnection #change #asian #enjoy #humid #singapore🇸🇬 #internship #care #cambodia #adventure #southeastasia #iphonex #iphoneonly #travel #travelphotography #temple #angkor #trip #angkorwat #siemreap #phnompenh #culture

node.text:
How time flies... 😅 
The Khao Sok National Park north of Phuket, unfortunately, was the last vacation of my six month internship in #Singapore 🙁
I‘m glad I was lucky enough to spend that last vacation with some of the best and most fun people I‘ve met in Singapore!
I think it was one of the best vacations I had while being here.

I can confidently say that the time in Singapore, together with the open minded people around me and the traveling, changed the way I see and approach different situations.

Before I go home to Germany, however, I have two more weeks of traveling through Cambodia and Vietnam planned. 
Let’s see what those two countries have to offer 😋

node.text:
Taiwan actually wasn’t one of the places I planned to visit while staying in Singapore but somehow my friend convinced me 😄 
I took 4 days off to be able to go there for a full 8 days of traveling... totally worth it! 😁

The night markets are probably my most favorite part of their culture. They are rough, busy, and loud... however they still have an incredible atmosphere and the good, smelly smell of stinky tofu 😂 😋 
Even though I‘m not a city person, Taipei was really pretty and I enjoyed the sightseeing there.
But of course the countryside and national park we visited in Hualien was much better.

All in all an absolutely stunning vacation with indispensable company ✌️ #vegan #veganfood #govegan #maketheconnection #change #asian #enjoy #green #tropical #humid #singapore🇸🇬 #internship #care #jungle #adventure #fruit #locals #rain #southeastasia #iphonex #iphoneonly #taiwan #taipei #taiwanese #enjoy #bestcompanion

node.text:
Kuching in Borneo kind of felt like we went there years after the touristic boom. 😅 
When we went hiking, we often found ourselves in front forkings where only one way was open since all the other ones weren’t „maintained“...
It’s a really nice island with a lot of nature and many animals, even though we couldn’t see them when we were hiking, that’s why I had to improvise the monkey picture 😂 
The name rainforest can also be felt once it starts raining, when we were on our way back from Bako National Park, we got hit by  massive rainfall.
The Semenggoh National Reserve was my least favorite part of the trip... Yes, you see Orang-Utans there, however the way they display their few animals to hundreds of people is neither natural nor species-appropriate 🙁 
All in all, the trip was really nice and another interesting place to see. I just feel like I need to go even „further“ into the countryside to really see natural areas and get the full experience without all the crappy touristic stuff 🙈 ✌️ #vegan #veganfood #govegan #maketheconnection #change #asian #enjoy #green #tropical #humid #singapore🇸🇬 #internship #care #jungle #adventure #fruit #locals #monkey #monkeys #rain #southeastasia #iphonex #iphoneonly #borneo #malaysia #forest #jungle #rainforest

node.text:
First short-trip that was not Malaysia or Indonesia 😄 Phuket, Thailand 🇹🇭 I was really confused about this city and country since everything was unexpectedly expensive, no idea why so many tourist come here. Indonesia is a fifth of the price and looks and feels very similar.
Even though I absolutely despise the way they treat Elephants, Monkeys, and other animals here, especially for tourist entertainment (I despise those tourists even more 😒), the vacation was amazing! 
The Thai cuisine is incredible, I just love the diversity of spices and herbs they use 😍 🌱 
After the really fun #vegan cooking class on Saturday I went for my very first surfing class on Sunday and, right away, decided to do a second class later that day 😄 🏄🏽 Already thinking about doing another weekend trip just for surfing 🙈 
All in all, Thailand seems to be a beautiful country that gets destroyed by to many careless tourists without respect for culture and nature... 🙁✌️ #veganfood #govegan #maketheconnection #change #asian #enjoy #green #tropical #humid #singapore🇸🇬 #internship #care #thailand #jungle #adventure #fruit #cooking #locals #southeastasia #iphonex #iphoneonly #thai #thaifood #tourism #surf #surfing #phuket

node.text:
I really like to mix traveling alone and with friends. Most times, traveling with people is more exhausting since everyone has their own favorite places and wants to do different stuff. 
It’s rare to find a group of people with whom everything fits... the food, the humor, the interests and the preferences 👌 
#yogyakarta is a nice place to go but to be honest, without a group like we were, I wouldn’t have enjoyed it that much 😅
Really unfortunate that we most likely won’t be able to make another trip with the same group 🙁 
Still enough time to have some nice evenings in #singapore together 🙌 
Hopefully I can find a way to stay in contact with the people once we are all back at home ✌️ #veganfood #govegan #maketheconnection #change #asian #enjoy #humid #singapore🇸🇬 #internship #care #indonesia #adventure #southeastasia #iphonex #iphoneonly #travel #travelphotography #temple #java #people #crew #trip

node.text:
I really don’t know how, but the Komodo National Park was a whole new level...
Didn’t know what to expect but got blown away completely! 😍
.
Upon arriving at the airport and being in the only airplane on the whole airport, I wasn’t sure if this is good or bad 😅 
The first impression of Labuan Bajo itself also was kind of, let’s call it „interesting“.
What surprised me most in the city is that they even had #vegan food. And it was damn delicious... like incredibly good 🤤 .
But once leaving the main Island with the boat and approaching the Komodo National Park, everything changed. The nature there is still so raw. Most of the islands seem to have no inhabitants at all.
No Hotels, no Homestays, just pure nature.
One local told me that the government still tries to keep the hotels away from the islands which is a really good thing 💪 .
From all the trips I did up to this point, this was probably the one most worth it. 👌 
Hadn’t have enough time to also see the Flores area so I might come back to see the incredible nature there, too 😋 ✌️ .

node.text:
Rawa Island wasn’t about seeing much pure nature but more about experiencing living on a small, quite tropical island with many of my co-interns. 
I really didn’t expect to find such a #tropical place in #malaysia 😅 
But well, yeah, seems like I was wrong. Already thinking about visiting Tioman together with other interns to do some diving in the incredible water there 😍 
Together, we were 21 people, I wasn’t really sure if that isn’t too many, but it was awesome and totally worth going there.
Next up is Kuala Lumpur for the elongated weekend coming next week and well, after that I‘ll had of to Komodo for even more days to visit the national parks there and do some diving.
Beautiful nature paired with good #vegan food and incredible people is how it should be, shouldn’t it? 😁✌️ #govegan #maketheconnection #change #asian #enjoy #green #humid #singapore🇸🇬 #internship #care #rawa #island #adventure #southeastasia #iphonex #iphoneonly #iphonephotography #people #snorkeling #kayak

node.text:
Bali was my very first trip alone. I wasn’t really sure whether it will work out since I really like being around people 😅 
3 quite exhausting days with tons of stuff to see and do, and of course #vegan food to eat 😂 🌱 🤤
Also decided to go for a local cooking farm at an #organic farm which was magnificent! Met some great people there and cooking together really gets you acquainted with each other 👌 
I talked to so many locals, this most likely would’ve never happened if I went here in a group.
Absolutely enjoyed this place (even though I tried to stay away from the biggest tourist spots and move up in the north 😅)

node.text:
Before I came to Singapore I was facing a though decision. Working for an incredible company that seemed to value their employees (even the interns) immensely or working at a great company I‘ve worked at before for less salary, no financial support with relocation etc. and no meals covered by the company, but the possibility to travel south-east Asia to the fullest. 
Well, the pics tell the outcome of the story. 😄 
I‘m only 3 weeks in but already met so many incredible people ( thank you so much for the incredible chat over dinner @debbiediscovers ) 😊 
Absolutely worth it! Couldn’t have made a better decision. 🙏 
Already looking forward to my short weekend trip to Bali next weekend 😋 
It will be a #vegan feast.

node.text:
It’s kind of weird, Singapore seems to really try to live as sustainable as possible, yet everywhere you go, you see plastic bags, cutlery, and plates and boxes made out of styrofoam 🙁 
It’s an incredible place which seems to be ahead of Germany in many things, but ecological sustainability is not yet one of them. #Singapore definitely needs more #vegans who care for the environment 😂 ✌️ Really looking forward to the next 6 months here and learning more about this place 🙌 🌱

node.text:
Sichuan dry-fried green beans😋 (Gan Bian Si Ji Dou '干煸四季豆'). If you love green beans, be sure to save this recipe👌🏻. If you don't, I urge that you give this aromatic bean a chance to be your next star dish😄. Green beans for Gan Bian Si Ji Dou are usually blanched in hot oil for a few minutes until the skins blister before tossing them with the sauce. So, check out the simplified & healthier steps to make this tasty meal below🙏🏻. Enjoy & have a lovely, Thursday, friends.🤗⁣ ⁣
Recipe (yields 2-3 servings)⁣
🌱Ingredients:⁣
~ 1 lb green beans⁣
~ 8oz firm tofu - drained, mashed, pan-fried & lightly seasoned with salt⁣
~ 3 teaspoons finely minced ginger⁣
~ 3 teaspoons finely minced garlic⁣
~ 3 dried/fresh chili - seeds removed, softened & cut in half⁣
~ oil, toasted sesame oil, salt to taste⁣
⁣
🌱Sauce: Mix together 1 tablespoon light soy sauce, 1/2 tablespoon stir fry sauce (check highlight for recipe) & 1 teaspoon sugar until all incorporated & set aside.⁣
⁣
✅Bring a pot of water to boil, blanch green beans quickly in hot water for 1 min. Drain green beans & wipe dry with a paper towel.⁣
✅Place green beans in a heated non-stick pan with 2 teaspoons of oil. While turning the beans constantly, pan-fry green beans over low-med heat until the skin is slightly blistered or wrinkly, about 8 mins. Be sure to keep the beans in a single layer for even cooking time. Transfer cooked beans to a plate. ⁣
✅Using the same pan, add 1 teaspoon oil, then sauté ginger & garlic until fragrant. Add dried chili, tofu & continue to cook for another minute, season with a pinch of salt.⁣
✅Then, add in the beans & sauce. Continue to sauté until beans are well coated with sauce or until the sugar has melted. Season accordingly & add a swirl of toasted sesame oil before serving. Serve warm with your favorite grain.⁣

node.text:
RED LENTIL CAULIFLOWER CURRY by @rie_mols ❤️
.
(Recipe adapted from @biancazapatka)
.
. (serves 4)
1 tbsp oil
1 onion
750g cauliflower bouquets (1 small or 1/2 big) 
75g red split lentils (dry) 
1 can (400g) tomatoes 
250 ml (about 1 cup) veggie broth
100g soy yogurt
1 tsp grated fresh ginger
1 tsp curry powder
1 tsp garam masala
1/2 tsp turmeric 
1/2 tsp paprika or chili
1/4 tsp cumin
1/2 tsp garlic powder
Salt and pepper to taste

Toppings
Roasted cashews, spring onion, lime and sesame seeds. 
Turn the stove on medium heat. When the frying pan is hot add 1 tbsp oil. Add in onions and all the spices and sauté for 3 minutes. Add in chopped cauliflower bouquets and sauté for 2 more minutes, until the onion is soft. Add in ginger and lentils and sauté for 1-2 minutes. Add in canned tomatoes and vegetable broth. Turn down to low/medium heat and let it simmer for about 20 minutes, or until the lentils and cauliflower are cooked. In the end add in yogurt or coconut milk. This will make the sauce more creamy. Serve with rice or quinoa, and top it off with a squeeze of lime, spring onions, sesame seeds and a pinch of chili flakes. Find a comfy place to sit and enjoy! #bestofvegan
